The forward model is defined as \[ \begin{aligned} y &= f(x) \\ \dot{y} &= \nabla f(x) \cdot \dot{x} \end{aligned} \] To obtain the first element of the gradient using the forward model we have to seed \(\dot{x}\) with \(\dot{x}=[1.0,0.0]\). In the forward mode the second element which gets added for Dual arguments stores the tangent. #[autodiff(df, Forward, Dual, Dual)]
fn f(x: &[f32], y: &mut f32) { ... } fn main() { let x = [2.0, 2.0]; let dx = [1.0, 0.0]; let y = 0.0 let dy = 0.0; df(&x, &mut dx, &mut y, &mut dy);
} In the returning case we would write similar code, note that in this case the second Dual refers to our return value. #[autodiff(df, Forward, Dual, Dual)]
fn f(x: &[f32]) -> f32 { ... } fn main() { let x = [2.0, 2.0]; let dx = [1.0, 0.0]; let (y, dy) = df(&x, &mut dx);
} Note that to acquire the full gradient one needs to execute the forward model a second time with the seed dx set to [0.0,1.0].

